bc-hash (1.0.3-1) stable; urgency=medium

  * perf(discovery): switch walk_parallel to raw syscall(SYS_getdents64)
    and pad worker_slot_t to a full cache line. Together, on warm cache
    /var/benchmarks (1069096 files, 19 GB) these changes cut the
    discovery-only time from 0.195 s to 0.150 s (−25%). End-to-end
    sha256 wall time drops from 7.31 s (1.0.2 README baseline) to
    ~2.98 s, xxh3 from 6.77 s to ~1.81 s (Ryzen 7 5700G, warm, 5-run
    median). Correctness: byte-exact parity with sha256sum / xxhsum
    -H3 / xxhsum -H128 on sampled groups.
  * refactor: consume libbc-io 1.1.0 dirent_reader and libbc-runtime
    1.1.0 error_collector; drop internal duplicates (~200 LOC).
  * Build-Depends: libbc-io-dev >= 1.1.0, libbc-runtime-dev >= 1.1.0,
    libbc-allocators-dev >= 1.1.0.

 -- Younes Benmoussa <younes.benmoussa@pm.me>  Tue, 21 Apr 2026 21:55:00 +0000

bc-hash (1.0.2-1) stable; urgency=medium

  * Build with -march=x86-64-v3 (AVX2+FMA+BMI2): enables xxhash AVX2
    accumulation path at runtime on Zen3/Haswell+ hosts.
  * perf(uring): drain CQEs in batch via io_uring_peek_batch_cqe instead
    of one-by-one wait_cqe. xxh128: -12.5%, variance reduced 16x on
    148k files / 3.2GB warm-cache benchmark.
  * bench: drop cksum reference (CRC-32 IEEE != CRC32C, comparison
    misleading). Fix REF_JOBS default to 8 physical cores. Fix SIGPIPE
    on find|head -1 in filter-gain section.
  * build: drop stale 'benchmarks' meson option (no benchmarks/ subdir,
    bench is driven by scripts/bench.sh).

 -- Younes Benmoussa <younes.benmoussa@pm.me>  Sun, 19 Apr 2026 18:00:00 +0000

bc-hash (1.0.1-1) stable; urgency=medium

  * Rebuild against libbc-concurrency 1.0.2.
  * Upstream dependency libbc-concurrency 1.0.2 replaces its atomic +
    futex worker signaling with pthread_mutex + condition variables to
    close residual ThreadSanitizer data races on gcc 13 ubuntu-24.04.
    bc-hash embeds libbc-concurrency statically, so picking up the fix
    requires a fresh build.
  * No bc-hash source changes beyond a debian-hardening fix for
    read(2) warn_unused_result in src/bench/bc_hash_throughput.c.
  * No measurable performance regression: sha256 1.85 s / crc32c
    1.02 s / xxh3 1.01 s / xxh128 0.99 s on 13 GB / 724 k files warm
    cache (5 runs).

 -- Younes Benmoussa <younes.benmoussa@pm.me>  Sun, 19 Apr 2026 16:00:00 +0000

bc-hash (1.0.0-1) stable; urgency=medium

  * Initial public release.
  * Parallel file-tree hashing: SHA-256 (SHA-NI accelerated),
    CRC32C (SSE4.2), xxh3, xxh128.
  * Lock-free MPMC directory queue with per-worker file accumulators.
  * Batched I/O via io_uring when available; synchronous fallback.
  * Adaptive single-threaded / multi-threaded dispatch based on
    auto-measured hardware throughput.
  * 'hash' and 'check' subcommands for digest production and
    verification; exclude/include path filters.
  * Graceful SIGINT / SIGTERM handling (<30ms exit, code 130).

 -- Younes Benmoussa <younes.benmoussa@pm.me>  Sun, 19 Apr 2026 12:00:00 +0000
